page.title: 03ECOLOGY-BIRDS AND MAMMALS
page.content: THE BIRD LIFE IS TYPICAL FOR THE {AGRICULTURAL LAND}IN N.E. NORFOLK E.G. SKYLARKS, WOODPIGEONS, PHEASANTS, ALL COMMON. ROOKS, DECLINING IN MANY AREAS OF NORFOLK ARE STILL PLENTIFUL DUE TO THE PRESCENCE OF TWO ROOKERIES AT BESSINGHAM. COMMON PARTRIDGE GREATLY DEPLETED IN NUMBERS AS ELSEWHERE, BUT RED-LEGGED PARTRIDGE STILL PLENTIFUL.{ {MAMMALS.}RABBITS STILL PRESENT IN SPITE PRESENCE OF MYXOMATOSIS. HARES PRESENT IN SPITE OF DECLINE IN MANY RURAL AREAS DUE TO MODERN METHODS OF AGRICULTURE. RED SQUIRREL SEEN IN WOODS, BACONSTHORPE IN{1985,}BUT NOW VERY RARE IN THE AREA HAVING BEEN COMMON UP UNTIL 10 YEARS AGO. GREY SQUIRREL IS SLOWLY REPLACING IT. ROE DEER STILL QUITE COMMON. {BOTANY.}NOTHING OF NOTE TO KNOWLEDGE {BY DOCTOR KEYMER.
